  abstract = {Background: Real-time (RT) imaging is beneficial for patients with poor breathholding and arrhythmias but is typically limited to 2D sequences. Furthermore, low-field systems intended for lower resource settings may lack gating equipment and trained CMR operators, making RT imaging appealing. We introduce an approach for 3D free-breathing ungated spiral bSSFP cine imaging using selfsupervised deep learning, with 36 ms and 58 ms temporal resolution per volume at 1.5T and 0.55T, respectively. Methods: A bSSFP sequence was used with stack-of-spirals1 golden angle sampling (Fig. 1A). A Time- and Partition-Dependent Deep Image Prior (DIP) is proposed that generalizes the TimeDependent DIP for 2D RT CMR.2,3 A convolutional neural network (CNN), without prior training, was optimized to generate 3D RT images. The CNN used 2D (not 3D) convolutions for computational efficiency. Time and partition dimensions were parameterized on a low-dimensional manifold. To generate an image for a given time frame and partition, the manifold was sampled and input to the CNN (Fig. 1B). This process was repeated for all frames and partitions to obtain 3D RT images. Fourier basis functions were chosen for the manifold; lower frequency sinusoids favored gradual changes in image content, while higher frequencies allowed recovery of rapid dynamics. The CNN was trained using a loss that enforced consistency with measured k-space data (Fig. 1C). Training took 26 hours on a GPU, performed de novo after each scan. Short-axis scans were acquired in 5 healthy subjects at 1.5T (Siemens Sola). 3D RT images were collected with 10.4s scan time, 16 partitions, 2.3x2.3x8.0 mm3, and 36 ms/volume. Data were also acquired using a 2D RT spiral scan (34 ms/image) with a Time-Dependent DIP and a 2D reference Cartesian breathheld ECG-gated scan. LVEF was compared using Bland-Altman plots after manual contouring. As a proof-of-concept, two of these subjects were scanned at 0.55T (Siemens Free.Max) using 2D and 3D RT sequences. Lower gradient performance resulted in temporal resolutions of 50 ms (2D) and 58 ms (3D). Results: Fig. 2 shows 2D reference, 2D spiral RT, and 3D spiral RT images from at 1.5T. Bland-Altman results for LVEF, reported as bias (95\% limits of agreement), were -0.9\% (-8.2\%, 6.4\%) for 3D RT vs 2D reference, -2.4\% (-12.0\%, 7.1\%) for 3D vs 2D RT, and 1.6\% (-7.1\%, 10.2\%) for 2D reference vs 2D RT. Fig. 3 shows 2D and 3D RT images from one subject at 0.55T. Conclusion: This study demonstrated the feasibility of 3D RT imaging using a Time- and Partition-Dependent DIP reconstruction. Whole-heart RT images were acquired in 10s without breathholds or gating, which could enable streamlined exams. 3D RT imaging may simplify LVEF quantification since motion is synchronized over all CMR 2024 The Global CMR Conference Journal of Cardiovascular Magnetic Resonance 26 (2024) 100101},
  langid = {english}
}

